{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513361"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:08:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:08:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12086"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12086"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.56,0.2,0.18,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4639"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87013"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4639"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12086"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71270"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7047"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7058"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87013"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of progressive tremor, slowed movements, and yellowing of his skin. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He does not drink alcohol or use recreational drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has generalised bradykinesia, rigidity in his limbs, and a resting tremor. There is scleral icterus and mild hepatomegaly with right upper quadrant tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal bilirubin: 34 \u00b5mol/L (2-20)\u003Cbr /\u003EAspartate aminotransferase: 86 U/L (5-37)\u003Cbr /\u003EAlanine aminotransferase: 99 U/L (5-42)\u003Cbr /\u003EProthrombin time: 12 seconds (11-13.5)\u003Cbr /\u003EViral hepatitis serology: negative\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following laboratory patterns would be most characteristic of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Low serum ceruloplasmin and low urinary copper concentrations","Low serum ceruloplasmin and elevated urinary copper concentrations","Elevated serum ceruloplasmin and low urinary copper concentrations","Elevated serum ceruloplasmin and elevated urinary copper concentrations","Normal serum ceruloplasmin and low urinary copper concentrations"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation strongly suggests Wilson\u0027s disease, with the combination of neurological features (bradykinesia, rigidity, tremor) and hepatic dysfunction in a young adult. Wilson\u0027s disease is an inherited disorder of copper metabolism caused by mutations in the \u003Cem\u003EATP7B\u003C/em\u003E gene, leading to copper accumulation in various tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow serum ceruloplasmin and elevated urinary copper concentrations\u003C/strong\u003E are diagnostic of Wilson\u0027s disease. This pattern occurs because the defective ATP7B protein cannot incorporate copper into ceruloplasmin (causing low serum levels) and cannot excrete copper into bile (leading to increased urinary excretion as an alternative pathway).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow serum ceruloplasmin and low urinary copper concentrations\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely in Wilson\u0027s disease, as copper overload invariably leads to increased urinary copper excretion. This pattern might be seen in conditions of copper deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated serum ceruloplasmin and low urinary copper concentrations\u003C/strong\u003E is the opposite of what occurs in Wilson\u0027s disease. While ceruloplasmin can rise as an acute phase reactant in inflammation, it is characteristically low in Wilson\u0027s disease due to the genetic defect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated serum ceruloplasmin and elevated urinary copper concentrations\u003C/strong\u003E might occur in acute copper poisoning but not in Wilson\u0027s disease, where the genetic defect prevents normal ceruloplasmin synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal serum ceruloplasmin and low urinary copper concentrations\u003C/strong\u003E would not explain this presentation. Although ceruloplasmin can occasionally be normal in Wilson\u0027s disease (particularly during inflammation), urinary copper is consistently elevated due to the inability to excrete copper through bile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional diagnostic features include Kayser-Fleischer rings (copper deposits in the cornea) and elevated hepatic copper content on liver biopsy. Early diagnosis is crucial as copper chelation therapy can prevent disease progression.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Wilson\u0027s disease is characterized by impaired copper metabolism due to ATP7B protein defect, presenting with hepatic, neurological, and psychiatric manifestations.","Low serum ceruloplasmin and elevated urinary copper are characteristic laboratory findings in Wilson\u0027s disease.","Kayser-Fleischer rings and elevated hepatic copper levels are additional diagnostic features of Wilson\u0027s disease."],"references":["Rodriguez-Castro KI, Hevia-Urrutia FJ, Sturniolo GC. Wilson\u0027s disease: A review of what we have learned. World J Hepatol. 2015 Dec 18;7(29):2859-70.","Mulligan C, Bronstein JM. Wilson Disease: An Overview and Approach to Management. Neurol Clin. 2020;38(2):417-432. doi:10.1016/j.ncl.2020.01.005"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71270"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12086"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71270"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-25T13:20:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-25T13:22:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4639"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87013"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings